A 'Viola pedata' is a species of wildflower belonging to the Viola genus. 
This flower is primarily found in North America. 
It features deeply lobed leaves and small, heart-shaped blossoms. 
The petals of 'Viola pedata' are usually blue or purple, but can also be white or pink. 
The flower blooms in the late spring and early summer. 
It typically grows in sandy or rocky soil, and is often found in open fields, meadows, and along roadsides. 
'Viola pedata' is also known as the birdfoot violet, named for the shape of its leaves.
